AGI -&nbsp;&nbsp; The United Nations Humanitarian Affairs Office (Unocha) launched an urgent appeal for $430 million to help the people of Zimbabwe, affected by the worst drought in the last forty years.<br> Approximately half of the country's population, estimated in 15 million people, urgently needs food and water. The humanitarian coordinator living in the UN country, Edward Matthew Kallon, said that about 7.6 million people in Zimbabwe need "save and livelihood" humanitarian assistance. &nbsp;<span> However, the agency has asked donors to finance assistance also for 3.1 million people residing in the most severely affected districts for the needs</span>à</span>à</span><span> next year.</span>
&nbsp;
The drought, triggered by the climate phenomenon El Nino, is devastating much of southern Africa, leaving men and animals desperately need water and food resources.<br> Zimbabwe, a country dependent on agriculture and a time exporter of food, is among the most affected by the serious lack of water.
&nbsp;
Corn crops, the country's basic food, for the 2023-24 season are estimated at about 700,000 tonnes, 70% less than the previous season.<br> Zimbabwe needs 2.2 million tonnes of corn annually to meet domestic demand, according to government estimates. The UN's appeal includes aid ranging from food assistance to money transfers and building wells powered by solar energy, which would provide drinking water to dying people and livestock, such as cattle, a fundamental source of food and work.

